column2: fullStatement
ELA
Argumentative Text: Evaluate arguments and reasoning.
Evaluate whether the structure chosen by the author makes the argument of a text convincing and engaging.
Determine whether the rhetoric of a text strongly and persuasively supports the author's point of view and purpose.
Delineate the arguments an author uses to advocate for social, economic, or political issues.
Delineate the reasoning used to support arguments made for advocacy of social, economic, and political issues.
Identify constitutional principles applied to issues in a text (e.g. the issue of free speech).
Identify the legal reasoning found in a text (e.g. the Brown v. Board of Education decision regarding the legality of "separate but equal").
Delineate the reasoning used to apply and support constitutional principles in a text (e.g. The Tennessee ratification of the 19th amendment in 1920).
Delineate the reasoning used to argue and support landmark legal cases (e.g. Miranda v. Arizona (1966)).
ELA
Argumentative Text: Identify opinions and reasons in a text.
Identify the points about a topic that the author makes in a text.
Identify the reasons and evidence an author uses to support a point.
Explain how an author uses reasons to support points in a text.
Explain how an author uses evidence to support points in a text.
ELA
Argumentative Text: Identify argument, claims, and evidence.
Determine the reasons and evidence that an author uses to support points of information in a text.
Identify which reasons and evidence support which points of information.
Trace the argument and claims in a text.
Evaluate the argument made in a text.
Identify the reasons and evidence that support the claims in a text.
Distinguish valid claims from claims that are not supported in the text.
ELA
Argumentative Text: Trace argument, claims, and evidence.
Trace the argument developed in a persuasive text.
Evaluate the argument developed in a persuasive text.
Trace the specific claims that support an argument in a text.
Evaluate the specific claims that support an argument in a text.
Distinguish claims that are supported by reasons and evidence from those claims that are not.
Evaluate whether or not there is relevant and sufficient evidence to support claims.
Recognize whether or not the evidence is irrelevant or insufficient to support claims.
ELA
Argumentative Text: Analyze the arguments and logic of a text.
Identify how a particular portion of an argumentative text develops and refines an author's claims.
Analyze in detail the development and refinement of an author's claims in an argumentative text.
Determine the point of view and the purpose of the author in writing an argumentative text.
Analyze how authors use rhetoric to advance their points of view and purposes.
Trace the argument and specific claims in a text.
Evaluate the argument and specific claims in a text.
Assess whether an argument uses valid reasoning.
Determine whether relevant and sufficient evidence supports an argument.
Identify whether an argument includes false statements and logical fallacies.
ELA
Digital Literacy: Use a variety of digital tools and documents.
Use information from illustrations and words in digital documents to demonstrate understanding of characters of a story.
With guidance and support from adults, use digital tools to collaborate with others.
Use information from illustrations and words in digital documents to demonstrate understanding of the setting of a story.
Use information from illustrations and words in digital documents to demonstrate understanding of events of a story.
Identify digital text features (e.g. electronic menus, icons).
Use digital text features to locate key details and information.
Use digital glossaries and beginning dictionaries to determine or clarify the meaning of words and phrases.
With guidance and support from adults, use digital tools to produce writing.
With guidance and support from adults, use digital tools to publish writing.
With guidance and support from adults, use digital tools to communicate with others.
Evaluate and use techonology.
Use both local and web-based technology to produce, publish, and update individual writing.
Use both local and web-based technology to produce, publish, and update shared writing projects.
Use both local and web-based technology to respond to ongoing feedback, new information, and further arguments.
Use different technologies, online platforms, and websites to compose, submit, and distribute writing.
Use technology to format writing and to include footnotes, citations, table of contents, and other text features required for a certain purpose or audience.
Maintain a minimum keyboarding speed of 50WPM at 95% accuracy.
Evaluate domains, search engines, and other online sources for their credibility, currency, authority, and security.
Launch online searches with the effective use of precise keywords, specific symbols, and other operators.
Use digital media strategically to enhance an audience's understanding and enjoyment of a presentation.
Digital Literacy: Use digital tools for writing.
Use search tools to locate digital information on a given topic.
With some guidance and support from adults, use technology, including the internet, to produce writing.
With some guidance and support from adults, use technology, including online tools, to publish writing.
Demonstrate sufficient command of keyboarding skills to type a minimum of one page in a single sitting.
Maintain minimum keyboarding speed of 20WPM at 95% accuracy.
Demonstrate sufficient command of mousing skills to move cursor, left click and point, double click a link, and drag and drop.
Search for a topic on the internet by using search engines and effective keywords.
Digital Literacy: Use technology to produce writing and collaborate.
With some guidance and support from peers and adults use technology, including the Internet, to produce writing.
Demonstrate sufficient command of mousing skills to navigate websites and documents.
With some guidance and support from peers and adults use technology, including the Internet, to publish writing.
Use technology, including the internet to begin to produce and publish writing independently at the high end of the grade band.
With some guidance and support from peers and adults use technology, including the Internet, to interact and collaborate with others in writing projects.
With some guidance and support from peers and adults use technology, including the Internet, to interact and collaborate with others in researching projects.
With some guidance and support from peers and adults use technology, including the Internet, to interact and collaborate with others in presenting projects.
Use technology, including the internet to begin to collaborate with others on projects independently at the high end of the grade band.
Demonstrate sufficient command of keyboarding skills to type a minimum of two pages in one hour.
Maintain minimum keyboarding speed of 25WPM at 95% accuracy.
Digital Literacy: Use technology in searching for information and in publishing.
Include formatting (e.g., headings), graphics (e.g., charts, tables), and multimedia when useful to aiding comprehension of the topic.
Use search terms effectively for digital sources.
Use technology that formats writing with indentation, line spacing, pagination, and other styles suitable to the text type and purpose.
Use technology to publish, share, and reproduce texts complete with illustrations, graphics, and other media.
Demonstrate sufficient command of keyboarding skills to type a minimum of three pages in a single sitting.
Maintain minimum keyboarding speed of 30WPM at 95% accuracy.

Demonstrate sufficient command of all mouse functionality (e.g. right, left, and double click, drag and drop, highlighting, mouseover) to edit documents, to respond in online forms, and to search internet sources.
Use technology to link to and cite sources.
Use technology to interact and collaborate with others.
Use technology to present relationships between information and ideas efficiently.
Digital Literacy: Use and evaluate digital tools and internet sources.
Use keyboarding, mousing, and word processing to produce, publish, and update individual writing products.
Maintain minimum keyboarding speed of 40WPM at 95% accuracy.
Use learning management systems, document sharing sites, and other online tools to produce, publish, and update group writing products.
Link to and to display information flexibly and dynamically through appropriate internet sources.
Run queries for digital sources by using keyword searches, quotations, and other search operators as well as by finding topical databases or search engines.
Determine the reliability and validity of digital sources based on currency, authority, and security of their sites.
Use digital media strategically to enhance an audience's understanding and enjoyment of a presentation.
ELA
Digital Literacy: Use a variety of digital tools.
Explore a variety of digital tools to produce and publish writing with guidance and support from adults.
Explore a variety of digital tools to collaborate with peers with guidance and support from adults.
Expository Text: Analyze complex expository texts.
Cite strong textual evidence to analyze explicit meaning found in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze complex relationships among individuals in an expository or argumentative text.
Explain how events and individuals interact and impact one another's development over the course of an expository or argumentative text.
Determine the meaning of general academic words and phrases in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Determine the meaning of domain-specific terms and phrases in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Determine the figurative and connotative meaning of words and phrases in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how an author chooses and refines figurative language over the course of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze the choice an author makes to stress either the literal or figurative meanings of words and phrases in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze the choice an author makes to stress either the denotation or connotation of words and phrases in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how an author develops the meaning of a key term or terms over the course of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Evaluate whether the structure chosen by the author makes the exposition of a text clear and effective.
Cite strong textual evidence to analyze inferences drawn from expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how an author's choice of writing style pertains to the content and contributes to the power and effectiveness of the text.
Compare and contrast the themes of seminal historical and public documents from different time periods.
Compare and contrast the purpose of authors who wrote seminal historical and public documents in different time periods.
Compare and contrast the rhetorical devices used in seminal historical and public documents from different time periods.
Determine those parts of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts that have unclear or uncertain ideas.
Determine whether expository, argumenative, or procedural texts have two or more central ideas.
State the central idea(s) of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Distinguish the relative importance and order of multiple central ideas found in expository, argumentative, and procedural texts.
Analyze how a complex set of ideas interact and build on one another in expository, argumentative, and procedural texts.
Provide an objective summary of expository, argumentative, and procedural texts including their central idea(s).
Analyze a complex sequence of events in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Expository Text: Interpret information and explanations about a topic.
Quote accurately from expository, argumentative, and procedural texts.
Recognize the difference between fact or evidence and opinion or judgment.
Provide a summary of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts distinct from personal opinion or judgement.
Explain the relationships and interactions between two or more individuals in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Explain the relationships and interactions between two or more events in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Explain the relationships and interactions between two or more ideas in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Explain the relationships and interactions in a series of historical events in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Explain the relationships and interactions of scientific concepts in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Explain the relationships and interactions between two or more technical procedures or steps in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Recognize examples given in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Recognize anecdotes given in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Cite textual evidence from expository, argumentative, and procedural texts.
Analyze in detail how examples and anecdotes introduce a key individual in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze in detail how examples and anecdotes introduce key events in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze in detail how examples and anecdotes illustrate and elaborate key events in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze in detail how examples and anecdotes introduce key ideas in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze in detail how examples and anecdotes illustrate and elaborate key ideas in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Identify which text structure is used to convey information in an expository text.
Compare and contrast the overall structure of two or more texts.
Analyze how a particular sentence, paragraph, chapter, or section fits into the overall structure of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how a particular sentence or paragraph develops the central idea of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how a particular chapter or section develops the central idea of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Cite accurate quotations from expository, argumentative, and procedural texts.
Determine the point of view and perspective of an author in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Determine the purpose of an author in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Explain how the point of view and perspective of an author is developed in the text.
Explain how the purpose of an author is developed in the text.
Recognize multiple accounts of the same event or topic found in different expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze multiple accounts of the same event or topic explaining important similarities in the perspectives of the authors.
Analyze multiple accounts of the same event or topic explaining important differences in the perspectives of the authors.
Explain how details and information convey the central idea in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Integrate information from several texts on the same topic in order to write or speak about the subject knowledgeably.
Compare several texts on the same topic to identify key details or ideas that are similar.
Use accurate quotations to explain the explicit meanings of expository, argumentative, and procedural texts.
Contrast several texts on the same topic to identify key details or ideas that are different.
Compare and contrast the presentation of events by one author with that of another author.
Cite expository textual evidence correctly to explain the explicit meanings of expository, argumentative, and procedural texts.
Draw inferences supported by evidence cited from expository, argumentative, and procedural texts.
Determine whether expository, argumentative, and procedural texts have more than one central idea.
Determine how particular key details support the central idea(s) in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Write a summary of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts which includes the central idea and key details.
Expository Text: Analyze text structure and evidence.
Cite textual evidence from expository, argumentative, and procedural texts.
Distinguish objective details and information from personal opinion when writing a summary of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Identify individuals, events, and ideas in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how ideas and individuals interact and influence each other in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how ideas and events interact and influence each other in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how events and individuals interact and influence each other in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how a text uses comparisons to connect individuals, ideas, and events in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how a text uses analogies to connect individuals, ideas, and events in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how a text uses categories to connect individuals, ideas, and events in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how analogies impact the meaning of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how analogies impact the tone of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Identify explicit textual evidence to support analysis of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how allusions from other texts impact the meaning of a literary text.
Analyze how allusions from other texts impact the tone of a literary text.
Determine which structure an author uses to organize an expository text.
Analyze how the parts contribute to the whole in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how major sections contribute to the development of the ideas in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze the structure of a specific paragraph in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Identify what role particular sentences of a paragraph have in the development of a concept.
Determine the perspective or position of the author in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Determine what perspectives other than those of the author are in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Compare and contrast the perspectives found in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Support inferences drawn from expository, argumentative, or procedural texts by using cited textual evidence.
Analyze how an author distinguishes his or her perspective or position from that of others expressed in a text.
Determine the point of view or purpose of the author in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Identify conflicting viewpoints in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how an author acknowledges and responds to conflicting evidence or viewpoints in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Compare and contrast how two or more authors present key information and evidence in texts about the same topic.
Analyze how two or more authors writing about the same topic differ in their emphasis on the evidence they present.
Analyze how two or more authors writing about the same topic differ in their interpretations of the facts they present.
Analyze the conflicting information and contrasting facts in two or more texts written on the same topic.
Analyze the conflicting interpretations in two or more texts written on the same topic.
Determine which textual evidence most strongly supports an analysis of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Determine the central idea in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze how key details convey and support the central idea in expository, argumentative, and procedural texts.
Analyze the development of the central idea over the course of expository, argumentative, and procedural texts.
Analyze the relationship of the central idea to supporting details in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Provide an objective summary of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Expository Texts: Evaluate expository texts.
Identify evidence that is explicitly stated in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Identify how an author orders, develops, and connects a series of ideas in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Identify how an author orders, develops, and connects a sequence of events in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze the order, development, and connections of ideas in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze the order, development, and connections of events in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Identify the tone that words and phrases create in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze the cumulative impact of specific word choices on tone in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Identify how a particular portion of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts develops and refines an author's ideas.
Analyze in detail the development and refinement of an author's ideas in a particular portion of text.
Determine the point of view and purpose of the author in writing expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Recognize the historical significance of seminal U.S. documents.
Identify inferences that can be drawn from specific textual evidence.
Interpret and analyze the historical significance of seminal U.S. documents.
Analyze the textual significance (e.g. theme, order of ideas, rhetoric) of seminal U.S. documents.
Compare and contrast similar themes and concepts addressed in different seminal U.S. documents.
Cite strong and thorough textual evidence to support the analysis of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Cite strong and thorough textual evidence for inferences drawn from the text.
Evaluate the extent to which specific evidence does or does not support the analysis of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Determine the central idea in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Analyze the development of the central idea over the course of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Determine how specific details shape and refine the central idea in expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Provide an objective summary of expository, argumentative, or procedural texts.
Fluency: Read texts in the 1-2 grade band.
Read a range of literary text types in the grade band 1-2.
Read and comprehend literature, including stories and poetry, in the grades 1-2 text complexity band proficiently, with scaffolding as needed at the high end of the range.
Read informative texts in the 1-2 grade band, with prompting and support.
Read and comprehend informative texts, including history/social studies, science, and technical texts in the 1-2 grade band proficiently, with scaffolding as needed at the high end of the range.
Read with sufficient accuracy and fluency for comprehension.
Read grade-level text with purpose and understanding.
Read grade-level text orally with accuracy.
Read grade-level text at the appropriate rate and with expression.
Reread as necessary.
Fluency: Comprehend literature and nonfiction in the 11-CCR grade band.
Read and comprehend literature, including stories, dramas, and poems, in the grades 11-CCR text-complexity band proficiently.
Read and comprehend literary nonfiction in the grades 11-CCR text-complexity band proficiently.
Fluency: Read texts in the 3-4 grade band.
Read and comprehend literature (e.g. stories, dramas, poetry) within the 3-4 text complexity band, with scaffolding as needed at the high end of the range.
Read with purpose: to be entertained, to be informed, or to be persuaded.
Read grade-level prose and poetry orally with accuracy, appropriate rate, and expression on successive readings.
Read and comprehend informative texts within the grades 3-4 text complexity band, with scaffolding as needed at the high end of the range.
Know and apply grade-level phonics and word analysis skills in decoding words.
Use letter-sound correspondences and syllabication patterns to read unfamiliar multisyllabic words in context.
Use knowledge of morphology (e.g., roots and affixes) to read unfamiliar multisyllabic words in context.
Decode words with common Latin derivational suffixes such as "able", "ation". and "ity" that form different parts of speech from root words.
Decode multisyllabic words.
Read grade-appropriate irregularly spelled words.
Read with sufficient accuracy and fluency to support comprehension.
Fluency: Comprehend literature in the 5-6 grade band.
Read and comprehend literature, including stories, dramas, and poems within the 5-6 text complexity band.
Read with suffcient accuracy and fluency to support comprehension.
Read grade-level text with purpose and understanding.
Read grade-level prose and poetry orally with accuracy, appropriate rate, and expression on successive readings.
Use context to confirm or self-correct word recognition and understanding, rereading as necessary.
By the end of the year, read and comprehend literary nonfiction in the 5-6 text complexity band.
Know and apply grade-level phonics and word-analysis skills.
Know and apply all letter-sound correspondences.
Know grade-level syllabication patterns.
Know grade-level word roots and affixes.
Decode multi-syllabic words using grade-level phonics and word analysis.
Decode multi-syllabic words using grade-level knowledge of syllabication patterns.
Decode grade-level words using knowledge of roots and affixes.
Fluency: Comprehend literature in the 7-8 grade band.
Read and comprehend literature, including stories, dramas, and poems, within the 7-8 text complexity band proficiently, with scaffolding as needed at the high end of the range.
Read and comprehend literary nonfiction within the 7-8 text complexity band independently and proficiently.
Fluency: Comprehend literature in the 9-10 grade band.
Read and comprehend literature, including stories, dramas, and poems, in the grades 9-10 text-complexity band proficiently, with scaffolding as needed at the high end of the range.
Read and comprehend literary nonfiction in the grades 9-10 text-complexity band proficiently with scaffolding as needed at the high end of the range.
Fluency: Listen to and read emergent-reader texts.
Listen to stories being read aloud with intent and purpose.
Listen carefully to stories being read aloud in order to answer questions about them.
Listen with intent and purpose to texts being read aloud.
Listen carefully to texts being read aloud in order to answer questions about them.
Read emergent-reader texts with purpose and understanding.
Grammar & Usage: Use the conventions of standard English grammar and usage.
Demonstrate command of the conventions of standard English grammar.
Use singular and plural nouns correctly.
Use singular nouns that agree with the verb in a basic sentence.
Use plural nouns that agree with verb in a basic sentence.
Identify personal pronouns.
Identify possessive pronouns.
Identify indefinite pronouns.
Use personal and possessive pronouns correctly.
Use indefinite pronouns correctly.
Identify collective nouns.
Use collective nouns correctly in the singular.
Demonstrate command of the conventions of standard English usage.
Identify frequently occurring irregular singular nouns.
Form and use frequently occurring irregular singular nouns (e.g. foot, child, tooth, mouse).
Identify frequently occurring irregular plural nouns.
Form and use frequently occurring irregular plural nouns (e.g., feet, children, teeth, mice, fish).
Identify reflexive pronouns. e.g., myself, ourselves).
Use reflexive pronouns (e.g., myself, ourselves).
Identify the present tense form of a verb.
Identify the past tense form of a verb.
Identify the future tense form of a verb.
Form and use the simple present tense of regular verbs.
Identify common nouns
Form and use the simple past tense of regular verbs.
Form and use the future tense of regular verbs.
Form and use the simple present tense of frequently occurring irregular verbs.
Form and use the simple past tense of frequently occurring irregular verbs.
Form and use the future tense of frequently occurring irregular verbs.
Use frequently occurring adjectives to modify nouns.
Use frequently occurring adverbs as modifiers.
Choose between the use of an adverb or adjective depending on what is to be modified.
Identify frequently occurring coordinating conjunctions.
Use frequently occurring coordinating conjunctions between two nouns and before the last noun in a list of items.
Identify proper nouns.
Use articles as determiners.
Identify demonstrative pronouns as determiners.
Use demonstrative pronouns as determiners.
Use frequently occurring prepositions of time, place, and direction.
Identify declarative sentences.
Identify interrogative sentences.
Identify imperative sentences.
Identify exclamatory sentences.
Write and add to a simple declarative sentence in response to a prompt.
Write and add to a simple interrogative sentence in response to a prompt.
Identify possessive nouns.
Write and add to a simple imperative sentence in response to a prompt.
Write and add to a simple exclamatory sentence in response to a prompt.
Compose simple sentences.
Identify compound sentences.
Use coordinating conjunctions in compound sentences.
Combine and rearrange simple sentences to compose compound sentences.
Compose and add to compound sentences.
Use knowledge of language when writing, speaking, reading, and listening.
Use knowledge of usage conventions when writing, speaking, reading, and listening.
Identify formal uses of English.
Use common and possessive nouns.
Identify informal uses of English.
Compare formal and informal uses of English in writing, speaking, and reading.
Identify singular nouns.
Identify plural nouns.
Distinguish plural nouns from possessive nouns.
Grammar & Usage: Have command of standard English.
Demonstrate a command of standard English grammar and usage in writing.
Comprehend meaning and recognize style when reading a text.
Comprehend meaning and recognize style when listening to a text.
Vary syntax within sentences for an intended effect in a text.
Vary the syntax in paragraphs to build relative relationships of time, comparison, and cause/effect.
Use the form of parallel structure that best supports the purpose of the text.
Correct mistakes in parallel structure by making parts of speech, types of phrases, and structures of clauses consistent.
Use subordinate clauses that best establish the relationship of ideas in a text.
Choose the order of subordinate and independent (main) clauses to clarify the relative importance of ideas in a text.
Use relative clauses as essential or nonessential modifiers that best provide descriptions in a text.
Identify and correct misplacement of relative clauses to make modification and meaning clear.
Demonstrate a command of standard English grammar and usage in speaking.
Place relative clauses effectively for the purpose of the text.
Revise sentences either to correct or to strengthen their pronoun/antecedent agreement.
Vary the subject of sentences with different phrases that function as nouns (e.g. noun phrases, infinitive phrases, gerund phrases).
Correct for subject and predicate agreement consistent with the mood, tense, and voice of the verb.
Correct the mood of the sentence in relationship to its structure.
Recognize the language conventions that are used over different periods of time.
Recognize the formal and informal conventions of language that are used for different purposes and audiences.
Choose and apply the language conventions most appropriate for a given task, purpose, and audience.
Consult references to resolve the complex or contested use of language conventions.
Understand how language functions in different contexts.
Make effective choices of language to convey the intended meaning in a text.
Make effective choices of language to create the intended style of a text.

Demonstrate command of the conventions of standard English grammar when writing or speaking.

Form and use irregular plural nouns as parts of phrases in particular sentences.
Recognize abstract nouns as parts of phrases in particular sentences.

Demonstrate command of the conventions of standard English usage when writing or speaking.

Use a subordinating conjunction to join an independent (main), and a dependent (subordinate) clause in a complex sentence.
Produce simple sentences.
Produce compound sentences.
Explain the function of nouns and pronouns in the subjects or objects of sentences.
Produce complex sentences.
Use relative pronouns (e.g. who, whose, whom, which, that).
Use relative adverbs (e.g.where, when, why).
Form the verb "to be" in the past, present, and future tense.
Form the present participle of a verb.
Use the verb "to be" and the present participle of a verb to form the progressive past, present, and future tenses.

Determine the correct verb tense to express an action.
Form and use the correct verb tense to express an action.

Use and form modal auxiliaries correctly to express a condition.

Recognize and correct run-on sentences.

Use knowledge of language and its conventions when writing, speaking, reading, or listening.
Recognize that certain situations call for the use of formal English.

Recognize and observe differences between the conventions of spoken and written standard English.
Recognize the differences between formal and informal English.
Differentiate between contexts that call for formal English and situations where informal discourse is appropriate.
Explain the function of adverbs as modifiers in particular sentences.
Form and use regular singular nouns as parts of phrases in sentences.
Form and use regular plural nouns as parts of phrases in sentences.
Recognize irregular plural nouns.

Demonstrate command of the conventions of standard English grammar when writing or speaking.
Recognize pronouns that are in the subjective case.

Correctly use contractions for pronouns in the subjective case and the verb phrases that follow them.
Recognize pronouns that are in the objective case.

Use the past perfect tenses correctly to show the relative time of actions in the past.
Use action verbs to convey various times and sequences.
Use linking verbs to convey various states and conditions.
